<page_title>An Experiment on an All-Hydrophobic Polypeptide</page_title>
<text>An Experiment on an All-Hydrophobic Polypeptide

[positive charge-red; negative charge-green; neutral-white; hydrophobic-pink; hydrophilic-cyan; water-blue; oil-yellow]
 
      

This model shows that a polypeptide all consisting of hydrophobic amino acids tend to fold into a globular structure in which its exposure to water is minimal. On the other hand, if put into oil, it will tend to stretch out in a line as much as possible, which corresponds to a conformation that has maximal exposure to the solvent.

Note that in vacuum, this chain also curls up because of the weak van der Waals attractions between the amino acids. Although final conformation may be similar to the case of it being in water, the speed of the folding process is faster in the latter case. The reason is that the polypeptide folds up in water primarily because of the interactions between amino acids and water molecules, but not because of the van der Waals attractions between amino acids.

   Related simulation: An all-hydrophilic polypeptide.
   Related simulation: A hydrophobic-hydrophilic-mixed polypeptide.
   Related simulation: Modeling hydrophobic and hydrophilic effects.</text>
